    <refentryinfo>
        <productname>&daps_command;</productname>
        <authorgroup>
            <author>
                <contrib>Developer</contrib>
                <firstname>Frank</firstname>
                <surname>Sundermeyer</surname>
                <email>fs@suse.de</email>
            </author>
        </authorgroup>
    </refentryinfo>
    <refmeta>
        <refentrytitle>&daps_command;</refentrytitle>
        <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
        <refmiscinfo class="date"><?dbtimestamp format="Y B d"?></refmiscinfo>
        <refmiscinfo class="version">&daps_version;</refmiscinfo>
        <refmiscinfo class="manual">daps</refmiscinfo>
    </refmeta>
    <refnamediv>
        <refname>&daps_init;</refname>
        <refpurpose>A command to set up a daps documentation directory</refpurpose>
    </refnamediv>
    <refsynopsisdiv id="daps_init.synopsis">
        <title>Synopsis</title>
        <cmdsynopsis>
            <command>&daps_init;</command>
            <arg choice="req">-d <replaceable>PATH_TO_DOC_DIR</replaceable></arg>
            <arg choice="opt">-r <replaceable>ROOT ELEMENT</replaceable></arg>
        </cmdsynopsis>
    </refsynopsisdiv>
    <refsect1>
        <title>Description</title>
        <para>&daps_init; is used in daps to create a new documentation project from scratch. It
            automatically sets up the key files and directory structure needed and creates an
            example document which can be used to explore dapsÂ´ functionality</para>
    </refsect1>
    <refsect1>
        <title>Options</title>
        <para>View the available Options with <command>&daps_init;</command></para>
        <para> Set the root element of your example dokument. Currently supported are "book"
            (default) and "article"</para>
        <cmdsynopsis>
            <command>&daps_init;</command>
            <arg choice="req">-r (article|book)</arg>
        </cmdsynopsis>
    </refsect1>
    <refsect1>
        <title>Examples</title>
        <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>Option usage example</term>
                <listitem>
                    <cmdsynopsis>
                        <command>&daps_init; -d /home/exampledir -r article</command>
                    </cmdsynopsis>
                    <para>This command creates a documentation poject in /home/exampledir with an
                        article as example document</para>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
                <term>Directory structure Example</term>
                <listitem>
                    <screen>
            EXAMPLE_DOC_DIR/ (1)
              |--DC* (2)
                 |--images/
                 |   |--src/ (3)
                 |   |--dia/
                 |   |--eps/
                 |   |--fig/
                 |   |--pdf/
                 |   |--png/
                 |   |--svg/
                 |--xml/ (4)
                    |--MAIN*.xml (5)
        </screen>
                    <orderedlist>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>"Working directory" for the respective documentation
                                project</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>DC-file defining the documentation project</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Top-level Directory for images used in the documentation. Contains
                                sub-directories for images in different formats</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>XML-file directory. Also holds entity declaration files</para>
                        </listitem>
                        <listitem>
                            <para>Main file of the documentation project. It contains references to
                                other books, chapters etc.</para>
                        </listitem>
                    </orderedlist>
                </listitem>
            </varlistentry>

        </variablelist>
    </refsect1>
